narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned more advanced single variable calc concepts, like Taylor series, integration techniques, and more advanced trig calculations.
Mainly I would say that I improved on solving integrals because so many chapters in the course incorporate integrals in one way or another.
Math
Refined knowledge of integrals
Learned the fundamentals of calculus.
I learned how to take integrals and how to think about math in a more abstract way than I had previously.
Calculus II materal, but I wouldn't say I learned them super well/thoroughly.
Calculus
Solid follow-up to first semester of calculus or calc AB. Covers integration techniques, sequence/series convergence, and calculus with parametric and polar equations.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The course was really well organized and I loved the consistency. The pre-class quizzes were great and were just the push I needed to start thinking about the concepts. Office hours were great (especially since there were so many opportunities to go). There were some inconsistencies with how well your TF/professor could explain the concepts.

The course facilitated learning very well. I liked that it was very structured; you could always find information about whatever you were looking for. Additionally, the course had a great support system. From your instructor to peer mentors, somebody was always available to go over your questions with you. I wasn't personally a big fan of pre-class explorations. I feel like it was a tedious additional form of work that I didn't really benefit from at all.
I think it went too fast and they should relook over the material they are teaching as the speed of class is a common complaint
There should be a curve in the class. I do not think it is fair to have such high weighted exams without an appropriate curve based on how everyone is doing in the class.

The math department should work on standardizing the class and the quality of professors. It was very evident that some students were at a large advantage compared to others depending on which section they were in.
my teacher was very unhelpful
The course is extremely formulaic and standardized, which is both a strength and weakness.
This course is well organized, focused, and the expectations are very clearly established.

Strengths: Lots of support with office hours, peer tutors, 1-on-1 tutors. Weaknesses: huge discrepancies between the TAs and the pace was unbelievable fast for those who were actually learning the material for the first time.
Needs more individual teaching
Very well organized with explorations/videos before class, a good textbook, and helpful lecture notes. Exam prep was streamlined by review sessions and past exam availability.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: If you're interested in math, I would recommend this! For most of us, this was just a prereq/distributional req, but I could see it being interesting if you want to learn more calculus.
I wouldn't say that this course was particularly interesting but if you need to take this for your pre-requisites then it is not a bad choice at all.
If you have to take it for pre-req or req
Yes--the instructors are responsive and the material is well-organized.
no, the teacher was not helpful

If you're willing to put in the work (it's not an overwhelming workload, just takes practice and asking questions), it's a very rewarding class.
